26:53.163 --> 26:55.225
Describe Particularly your freshman year if you 
can. But what was the typical routine for you on a

26:57.784 --> 27:02.492
class day? What time did you get up? What did you do? 
When? I guess the whistle started blowing at, I

27:04.576 --> 27:11.208
don't know, I guess it was damned early. It seemed 
like to me six, I'm guessing.

27:16.535 --> 27:20.500
would put on a uniform, double-check each other, 
make sure there weren't any smudges. Did you have

27:20.941 --> 27:25.066
any upperclassmen's room you had to care for that 
fish year? No. And then I went out on the hall to be in

27:27.670 --> 27:35.520
the squad that you were in, and then some, you know, 
sophomore comes by. We use nice terms for the

27:35.540 --> 27:37.583
archives. Some sophomore would come by, check us 
all, scream as all of us. We were fortunate in my

27:41.829 --> 27:45.073
squad that we had this one kid named Merritt, I 
don't think he was there after the first semester.

27:49.307 --> 27:52.771
But he just delighted in wearing white socks with 
his uniform. And they screamed at him all the time.

27:55.454 --> 27:56.596
And he just loved it. I was not one that was big on 
loving that. But they screamed at him most times.

28:01.042 --> 28:02.083
So anyway, we'd go out there. They'd inspect us, 
ask us a lot of questions, ask us what was on the

28:02.123 --> 28:15.280
inscription on Guyon Hall, the inscription on 
Lawrence Sullivan Ross, all this kind of stuff,

28:02.123 --> 28:15.280
the definition of a freshman, all this kind of 
stuff, all of which I still remember. and then went

28:16.120 --> 28:20.047
out into formation in the quad. Corps staff walked 
by. We marched to Mourning Child, did that bit,

28:22.131 --> 28:32.070
came back, cleaned up your room, got it ready for 
inspection in case somebody was going to come by.

28:32.860 --> 28:35.945
And then went to class. And for the first semester 
of our fish year, we were required to come back for

28:36.686 --> 28:43.256
noon. They did away with that because classes just 
didn't start matching after the first semester,

28:43.296 --> 28:48.904
which I thought was great. One more time, I didn't 
have to go in that place. And usually we'd go to

28:51.508 --> 29:00.842
class until then, and then I would always have some 
meat that night. At the end of my freshman year, a

29:01.497 --> 29:17.834
bunch of guys in the outfit, there was a guy named 
Kirby Brown, who is now the Director of Public

29:01.497 --> 29:17.834
Relations for Parks and Wildlife, was a fish class 
president then. Some guys in my outfit came to me

29:19.015 --> 29:25.362
and some upperclassmen said, hey, you ought to run 
for sophomore class president. I said, what makes

29:26.388 --> 29:28.732
you think I'm uniquely qualified to do that? And he 
said, well, your name, Sharp, you can do so much

29:28.752 --> 29:32.578
with it. And I said, yeah, you know, I bet that's 
right. You know, everybody's always asking me,

29:35.303 --> 29:38.067
are you Sharp, Chris Sharp, and all this kind of 
stuff? He said, yeah, you've got a great name. And

29:39.329 --> 29:42.094
so there were four or five people running. So I put 
my name in, and we printed up a bunch of signs that

29:42.114 --> 29:47.263
said, look Sharp, think Sharp, vote Sharp. And we 
plastered them all over the corps. Didn't put them

29:51.143 --> 29:52.605
anywhere else. You know, I don't know if anybody 
else voted for me on the civilian side. But then

29:56.550 --> 29:58.071
won. And then in that, then got to know Caperton and 
Lane Cruz and all of those folks. That was kind of a

30:06.141 --> 30:10.687
whole new world because I was also in the student 
senate at the time. And then at the end of my

30:10.787 --> 30:18.716
sophomore year, ran for student life chairman, 
which I guess, I don't know if they still have that

30:10.787 --> 30:18.716
or not. It's kind of a cabinet deal. And then, and 
Roger Miller was student body vice president, who

30:21.113 --> 30:27.821
was real close to Kent. And Roger and I met once a 
week and told each other we wouldn't run against

30:28.322 --> 30:31.566
each other. Both of us knew the line. And then when 
the time came, sure enough, Roger and I ran against

30:34.149 --> 30:39.476
each other for student body president. And Roger 
made one very terrible mistake, and that is the

30:39.656 --> 30:49.568
week before the election, we were both being 
interviewed by the battalion. And they asked

30:50.442 --> 30:56.490
Roger, I said, Roger, would you be willing to 
consider any alternatives to the bonfire? And

30:56.931 --> 31:03.159
Roger, being the open-minded kind of guy that he 
is, said, well, yeah, I'd consider some

30:56.931 --> 31:03.159
alternatives. And they asked me, and I said, well, 
of course not. That's heresy. Wouldn't do it and

31:07.225 --> 31:08.587
all this kind of stuff. And that was it. I mean, I 
could have gone fishing that last week because it

31:09.949 --> 31:13.193
was over with then. Do you remember what the margin 
was in the election? It was pretty serious. I mean,

31:19.296 --> 31:22.225
the Corps was really being sensed. The Corps and 
Walton Hall and Hart Hall and all those people.

